cracies, and the incorporation of kinship relations into migration logics, are the product of complex debates that attended colonial migrations. By charting how state control of migration was critical to the transformation of a world dominated by empire-states into a world dominated by nation-states, Mongia challenges positions that posit a stark distinction between the colonial state and the modern state to trace aspects of their entanglements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aContract system (Labor)zIndiaxHistory. 0aContract systemzIndiaxHistory. 0aPassportsxGovernment policyzIndiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822372110zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372110423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372110/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles